<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">Judgement which granted the Motion of the plaintiff's Counsel, upon which M<sup>r</sup> Cochrane addressing himself particularly to M<sup>r</sup> Judge Mabane said that "It was in vain to look for <span class="DelHand-author">that</span> Justice in that Court when the first Judge thereof brought in his pocket Judgements <span style="text-decoration:underline;">ready cut and dry</span> before they heard the opposite party."</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Copy of the Judges Comments on M<sup>r</sup> Jones's answer to the Special Interrogatory put to him by M<sup>r</sup> Ogden.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">"This Witness (meaning M<sup>r</sup> Jones) in his <span class="DelHand-author">special int</span> answer to the special interrogatory put to him by M<sup>r</sup> Ogden asserts <span style="text-decoration:underline;">facts which are directly contrary to the Record</span> &amp; <span style="text-decoration:underline;">therefore contrary to Truth</span>, for by the record it appears that on the 7<sup>th</sup> of June 1783 the Sol<sup>r</sup> General made a motion grounded on facts of a very serious &amp; important Nature in the Cause instituted by him at the instance of His Excellency General Haldimand for the Crown against the Honble John Cochrane agent to the remitters of the public Money which the Court ordered to be communicated by the Solicitor General to M' Panet &amp; <span style="text-decoration:underline;">that the same should be considered of by the Court</span>.  On the 11<sup>th</sup> June the Sol<sup>r</sup> General moved for Judgement upon his</p>

